{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512427"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:54:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:54:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11894"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583596"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:20:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:20:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11894"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11894"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.05,0.03,0.68,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4491"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43787"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4491"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11894"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28776"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"655"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1614"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"6190"},{"type":"tags","id":"6210"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6590"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26922"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42678"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43278"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43787"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with a five-day history of persistent back pain. This came on suddenly and the pain radiates down her left leg. She has difficulty walking. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, there is an area of localised tenderness over the L5/S1 spinous processes. Nerve root compression in this region is suspected.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the additional physical signs is most likely to be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Loss of knee jerk","Wasting of soleus muscles","Wasting of quadriceps muscles","Absent ankle jerk","Absent sensation on medial aspect of foot"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s acute-onset back pain that radiates to the limb raises the suspicion for radiculopathy. Nerve root compression and tenderness at the L5/S1 area points towards S1 radiculopathy. S1 radiculopathy presents with a radicular pain in the back that radiates to the posterior aspect of the leg and the foot. It is associated with motor and sensory deficits. The sensory deficits involve the dorsolateral thigh, dorsolateral lower leg, and lateral foot. The motor deficits lead to loss of foot eversion (due to weakness of peroneus longus and brevis muscle) and loss of plantarflexion (due to weakness of gastrocnemius). The ankle reflex is mediated by S1 and S2 nerve supply. Hence, S1 radiculopathy leads to \u003Cstrong\u003Eloss of ankle reflex\u003C/strong\u003E. The other reflexes and the nerve roots mediating them are listed below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatellar reflex is mediated by L3 and L4.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBiceps reflex is mediated by C5 and C6.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETriceps reflex is mediated by C6 and C7.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECremasteric reflex is mediated by L1 and L2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnal wink reflex is mediated by S3 and S4.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELoss of \u003Cstrong\u003Eknee jerk\u003C/strong\u003E would be associated with a higher nerve root lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWasting of soleus and quadriceps muscle\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly associated with post-trauma immobilisation. Even in those cases, muscle atrophy is caused by prolonged immobilisation. A five-day history is unlikely to lead to muscle wasting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe sensory supply of the medial foot is provided by the saphenous nerve (L3, L4) and medial plantar nerve (L4, L5). As S1 supplies sensory supply to the lateral foot this is unlikely to cause \u003Cstrong\u003Eabsent sensation on medial aspect of foot.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["An absent ankle jerk is consistent with an L5/S1 radiculopathy."],"references":["Berry JA, Elia C, Saini HS, Miulli DE. A Review of Lumbar Radiculopathy, Diagnosis, and Treatment. Cureus. 2019;11(10):e5934. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6858271/","Allegri M, Montella S, Salici F, Valente A, Marchesini M, Compagnone C et al. Mechanisms of low back pain: a guide for diagnosis and therapy. F1000Research. 2016;5:1530. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27408698/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28776"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11894"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},